I"	<p>For a long time I have been wanting to setup a personal blog where things can get organized and customized at the same time.
However it was just too time consuming, with all the DB setup, servers, deployment, etc.</p>

<h2 id="githut-pages--jekyll">Githut pages + Jekyll</h2>

<p><strong>A blog with PURE content</strong></p>

<p>I discovered <a href="https://help.github.com/en/github/working-with-github-pages/creating-a-github-pages-site">Githut pages</a>, and found it simple enough and yet flexible in terms of styles.
Once setup, it allows you to focus purely on the content which is Markdown, also it’s possible to write in offline mode. Publishing content is as easy as “git commit &amp;&amp; git push”</p>

<p>Thanks to <a href="https://medium.com/20percentwork/creating-your-blog-for-free-using-jekyll-github-pages-dba37272730a">blog post by Arya Murali</a></p>

<p><strong>Setup in 4 step</strong></p>

<ol>
  <li>setup a repo for the blog site
<code class="highlighter-rouge">https://github.com/&lt;github_username&gt;/&lt;repo_name&gt;</code></li>
  <li>source for a <a href="https://jekyllrb.com/docs/themes/">Jekyll theme</a> of your choice</li>
  <li>clone the repo locally, cd into it, git init, customize it and commit locally</li>
  <li>publish the site from branch gh-pages (default name to allow github pages build your site automatically)</li>
</ol>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="c"># create a local branch gh-pages</span>
git checkout <span class="nt">-b</span> gh-pages
git remote add origin &lt;repo_url_in_step_1&gt;
git remote <span class="nt">-v</span> <span class="c"># verification of remote</span>

<span class="c"># push gh-pages into remote repo</span>
git push origin gh-pages
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>If done correctly, the site will be available at
<code class="highlighter-rouge">https://&lt;github_username&gt;.github.io/&lt;repo_name&gt;/</code></p>

<p>After step 3, to test the site locally @ http://127.0.0.1:4000/, run:</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>bundle <span class="nb">install
</span>bundle <span class="nb">exec </span>jekyll build
bundle <span class="nb">exec </span>jekyll serve
</code></pre></div></div>
